data.content:
Here's how to replace those `Assert.IsTrue` calls with proper MSTest assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));  // this one is fine — no built-in "assert all"
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` or `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` — MSTest lacks `IsNotEmpty` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` — gives actual vs expected on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` — clearer failure message |

**MSTest's `CollectionAssert`** class is available for `ICollection` types:

```csharp
CollectionAssert.AllSatisfy(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));  // MSTest v3+
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expectedList, actualList);       // same order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, actualList);  // any order
```

> **Tip:** `Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` is almost always better than `Assert.IsTrue(actual == expected)` because it prints both values on failure instead of just "Expected: True, Actual: False".
